Comparisons between Ap54 and Ap27

Periklis Kontoroupis

November 15th, 2018

Summary of analysis

I selected 12 particles each corresponding to a different endemic setting, allowed 1000 repeated simulations and also kept the population size fixed at 440.

For the Ap27 I tested two cases for the female worm: mating cycle=“1” (gonot_cycle_1), mating cycle=“2” (gonot_cycle_2).

For the Ap54 I tested three cases: mating cycle=“1” (gonot_cycle_1), mating cycle=“1” (gonot_cycle_2) and in a seperate set of simulations I tested the timing of the reaper. The latter is tested since it simulates similar population size as in Ap27 and this is used as reference for the demography.

Results are presented by taking the average of outputs and also using the individual simulation runs. I used the outputs at pre-control (year 2000), 10yr and 15yr after the end of the last MDA given in 2014.

Summary of results: (A) summary of average model output (log files), (B) demography, (C) worm load by age, (D) worm prevalence by age, (E) mf count by age, (F) mf prevalence by age, (G) mf intensity by age, (H) parameter space diagnostics for 100,000 particles for ap54

What has changed from Ap27 to Ap52

  1. Fix on the female worm insemination period

  2. The reapEvent is scheduled correctly in Ap54: (the reaper visits the population just before the surveillance event), the reaper is working more effectively

  3. The random number generator engine is now based on a the java engine and not the Mersenne twister

  4. Demography has changed, the birth-rates are now different.

  5. Alot of optimizations…

What has changed from Ap52 to Ap54

  1. The age class < 5 is not properly initialized in 1850 which does not explain the differences at the first surveillance event (in 1980) though.

  2. Fixed a bug in reporting: it was due to truncating age (as a double) to an integer and after that looking up the age class which is 0 for 0 thru 5 (should be to 5, i.e. 0,1,2,3,4).

So it was not an error in any basic mechanism but a lookup error of the age class….

  1. fix of a bug that caused very occasional NaNs on the standardized prevalence

Scenario specification

Simulation characteristics (scenario 158):

Simulation start : year 1850

No MDA : year 2000, 2001, 2002

MDA (65%, annual,IA) : year 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011

No MDA : year 2012

MDA (65%, annual,IA) : year 2013, 2014

No MDA : year 2015 - 2030

Running options on Ap27 and Ap54

Ap27:

For the avg.bat I used:

start /wait /min java -cp .;wormsim.jar;colt.jar Onchosim2.Wormsim -avg -i%1 -r%2-%3

exit

For the run.bat I used:

start /wait /min java -cp .;wormsim.jar;colt.jar Onchosim2.Wormsim -run -i%1 -r%2-%3 -d

exit

Ap54:

For the run.bat I used:

java -Xms400m -Xmx400m -XX:+UseG1GC –add-modules java.xml.bind -cp .;wormsim.jar;colt.jar;commons-math3-3.6.1.jar Wormsim -run -iscenario_158_1 -r0-999 -d

java -Xms400m -Xmx400m -XX:+UseG1GC –add-modules java.xml.bind -cp .;wormsim.jar;colt.jar;commons-math3-3.6.1.jar Wormsim -avg -iscenario_158_1 -r0-999

Special note from Roel on population difference between ap27 and Ap52 at baseline (tested)

As far as I can see now, this is an error in all previous versions, and Ap52 is OK.

The error is very likely in the timing of the reaper.

In Ap52, the reaper visits the population just before the surveillance event (delay = -3 hrs for the reaper and -2 hrs for the surveillance event).

When resetting the simulation, the reapEvent is scheduled correctly in Ap54, but not in previous versions.

In previous versions, the reaper comes at a delay of +1 hour irrespective of what was specified in the input.

I am not 100% certain about this, but at least 99% :-)

Could you test if setting the delay of the reaper to -1 (i.e. just after the surveillance event) in Ap54 makes the difference disappear?

Thats what I did and confirmed his suggestion.

(B) Demographics:

Same notes on the demographics

I checked the different versions, the area under the curve is the same.

According to Roel, the reaper removes 5% of the population if pop size > 440. This means that the part of the more or less Gaussian distribution of Ap52 with the reaper after the survey moment (-1h) that is to the right of 440 moves to the left by 22 and is added to the part to the left of 440 (which is not affected). Adding these two distributions (the original until 440 and the part from 440 shifted to the left by 22) results in a more or less uniform distribution

Also about the Gaussian distribution with the reaper at -1: the Gaussian distribution is due to ‘regression to the mean’. The population size are influenced by random processes such as birth and death. ‘Regression to the mean’ simply means that extremes disappear.
